[Note that the case mentioned in the media report in section [1] above is not reflected in this weekly GPEI update. As the local media in Pakistan has been good at reporting on positive polio cases (and not necessarily as yet unconfirmed cases of AFP - acute flaccid paralysis), we suspect that this case will appear in future weekly GPEI updates.

As mentioned in previous posts related to the ongoing outbreak of cVDPV2 associated polio in Syria, there were a total of 65 identified cases of AFP in the affected region of whom 22 had been ruled out (not due to poliovirus). With the above confirmation of 2 new cases there have now been 24 confirmed cases of paralytic poliomyelitis attributable to the cVDPV2. There are also an addition 6 individual who were tested as part of contact tracing that were found to have asymptomatic cVDPV infections.

The above report from the GPEI confirms the media report from yesterday's ProMED-mail report on a 2nd case in Raqqah, confirming that the cVDPV2 responsible for this outbreak is now circulating in Raqqah governorate.

The WHO/GPEI map showing the locations of all confirmed cases of poliomyelitis in 2017 (and linkable to 2016) can be found at: http://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/.

For a map of Syria showing provinces, see http://www.emapsworld.com/images/syria-provinces-map.gif. Deir Al Zour is referred to as Dayr az Zawr in this map.

The HealthMap/ProMED map of Syria can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5155739,86. - Mod.MPP]
